h laws should apply in addressing problems within. Kirshner brings together theory with the discussion of specific cases and legal developments to explore this developing area of law. Looking at the key issues that arise in cross-border proceedings, International Bankruptcy offers a guide to this legal environment. In addition, she explores how globalization has encouraged the creation of new legal practices that bypass national legal systems, such as the European Insolvency Framework and the Model Law on Cross-Border Insolvency of the United Nations Commission on International Trade Law. The traditional comparative law framework misses the nuances of these dynamics. Ultimately, Kirshner draws both positive and negative lessons about regulatory coordination in the hope of finding cleaner and more productive paths to wind down or rehabilitate failing international companies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aBankruptcyvCase studies. 0aBankruptcy-Case studies. 0aBusiness failuresxLaw and legislation. 0aBusiness failures-Law and legislation. 0aConflict of lawsxBankruptcy. 0aConflict of laws-Bankruptcy. 0aLaw and globalization. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh  aEuropean Insolvency Regulation.  aUNCITRAL Model Law.  abankruptcy.  achoice of law.  acomplex corporate groups.  across-border restructuring.  aglobalization.  ainsolvency.  ainternational trade.  alegal harmonization.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311068858040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226532028423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226532028/original  a978-3-11-068858-0  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles